WEBVTT

00:00:00.210 --> 00:00:04.230
Welcome my friend to today's
lecture on data sufficiency.

00:00:04.710 --> 00:00:07.110
Let's decode this concept like detectives.

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:09.780
Concept explanation.

00:00:10.290 --> 00:00:13.200
So what is this data sufficiency you ask?

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:19.110
It's a crucial topic in quantitative
aptitude that tests a very special skill.

00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:24.900
The goal isn't to find the right answer,
but to figure out if you even have

00:00:24.930 --> 00:00:27.150
enough information to find the answer.

00:00:27.715 --> 00:00:32.394
It's like a detective asking, do I
have enough clues to name the culprit?

00:00:32.574 --> 00:00:34.224
Not who is the culprit.

00:00:34.765 --> 00:00:37.165
You get a question and two statements.

00:00:37.435 --> 00:00:41.964
Your mission should you choose
to accept it is to decide if one,

00:00:42.144 --> 00:00:46.194
both or neither of these statements
is enough to solve the mystery.

00:00:46.644 --> 00:00:49.224
It's all about logical
deduction, my friend.

00:00:50.010 --> 00:00:54.269
Real world relevance and don't
think this is just for your exam.

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:57.390
As an officer, you'll be swimming in data.

00:00:57.780 --> 00:00:59.730
This skill is your life jacket.

00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:04.050
It teaches you to quickly see if
you have enough information to

00:01:04.050 --> 00:01:08.130
make a solid decision stopping
you from making a mess of things.

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:13.170
Imagine looking at financial reports,
customer data, or market trends.

00:01:13.585 --> 00:01:17.845
Data sufficiency is what helps you
make accurate judgements without

00:01:17.845 --> 00:01:19.405
getting lost in the numbers.

00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:21.870
Breakdown of question types.

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:26.490
Now, what kind of mysteries
will you be solving based on

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:28.110
past patterns in your exam?

00:01:28.290 --> 00:01:31.500
These questions love to dress
up in different costumes.

00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:37.200
About 20% of the time they pop up from the
number system and simplification world.

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:40.530
Testing you on number
properties and basic math.

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:45.060
Another 15% come from averages,
ratios, and proportions.

00:01:45.899 --> 00:01:51.479
Then you have another 15% disguised as
percentages profit and loss problems.

00:01:51.869 --> 00:01:57.179
The biggest chunk around 20% is
from time, work and speed distance.

00:01:57.570 --> 00:02:02.609
And of course we can't forget menstruation
and geometry and algebra and equations

00:02:02.850 --> 00:02:05.399
each taking up about 10% of the stage.

00:02:05.789 --> 00:02:10.199
Finally, probability and permutations
and combinations also make a

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:12.329
guest appearance with a 10% share.

00:02:12.690 --> 00:02:14.100
Quite a party, isn't it?

00:02:14.834 --> 00:02:16.214
Formulas and tricks.

00:02:16.665 --> 00:02:21.524
Now for the secret sauce, the tricks,
while the specific formulas change

00:02:21.524 --> 00:02:26.174
with the topic, like profit loss or
time work, the real magic for data

00:02:26.174 --> 00:02:28.304
sufficiency is about your approach.

00:02:28.785 --> 00:02:32.589
The biggest trick is to stop yourself
from actually solving the problem.

00:02:33.605 --> 00:02:40.115
I know it feels wrong, but your only job
is to check if it can be solved always.

00:02:40.235 --> 00:02:44.855
And I mean, always check statement
one alone, then statement two alone.

00:02:45.335 --> 00:02:49.025
This helps you eliminate options
faster than a rumor spreads.

00:02:49.625 --> 00:02:52.535
Only combine them if they
both fail on their own.

00:02:53.075 --> 00:02:55.805
The goal is to find a
unique single answer.

00:02:56.285 --> 00:02:59.855
If a statement gives you one
solid answer, it's sufficient.

00:03:00.335 --> 00:03:04.685
If it gives you a, maybe this,
maybe that situation, it's useless.

00:03:05.255 --> 00:03:09.935
Also, watch out for sneaky, redundant
information where both statements

00:03:09.935 --> 00:03:14.525
are just saying the same thing in
different clothes and a golden rule.

00:03:14.735 --> 00:03:18.395
Don't use your own gun
stick only to what's given.

00:03:19.185 --> 00:03:20.415
Methods of solving.

00:03:20.895 --> 00:03:23.895
So how do we tackle these
beasts systematically?

00:03:24.225 --> 00:03:28.005
First, understand the question,
what are they really asking for?

00:03:28.275 --> 00:03:29.715
What is the target value?

00:03:30.135 --> 00:03:35.295
Next, analyze statement one alone,
pretend statement two doesn't even exist.

00:03:35.745 --> 00:03:37.755
Can you get a single definite answer?

00:03:38.115 --> 00:03:39.645
If yes, it's sufficient.

00:03:39.945 --> 00:03:44.115
If no it's not, then do the
same first statement, two alone.

00:03:44.505 --> 00:03:49.425
Forget everything you saw in statement
one is statement two, enough on its own.

00:03:49.935 --> 00:03:55.305
If neither of them works alone and only
then you can bring them together, combine

00:03:55.305 --> 00:03:57.405
their powers like a superhero came up.

00:03:57.885 --> 00:04:00.765
If together they give you
a unique answer, great.

00:04:01.215 --> 00:04:05.325
If they still leave you guessing, then
even together, they are not sufficient.

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:09.730
Finally, you pick the option that
matches your brilliant analysis,

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:12.220
shortcuts, and smart techniques.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:14.490
Want to be even faster.

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:16.590
Use the elimination strategy.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:21.480
If you find that statement one alone is
sufficient, you can immediately throw

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:23.610
out any option that says it's not.

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:29.100
Another smart technique is to focus on
variables, see what you need to find,

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:33.570
and then check if the statements give you
enough independent equations to find it.

00:04:34.159 --> 00:04:38.210
For some questions, especially
with inequalities, you can test a

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:42.469
couple of values if different test
values give you different answers.

00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:46.880
The statement is insufficient,
and please practice with a timer.

00:04:47.299 --> 00:04:50.000
It trains your brain to
assess, not calculate.

00:04:50.450 --> 00:04:54.710
Finally learning to categorize the
question type, algebra, geometry,

00:04:54.710 --> 00:04:58.015
et cetera, helps you recall
the right concepts in a flash.

00:04:59.130 --> 00:05:01.320
Common mistakes and misconceptions.

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:04.710
Now, let's talk about the
traps people fall into.

00:05:05.159 --> 00:05:08.850
The number one mistake is actually
solving the entire problem.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:09.810
Don't do it.

00:05:10.170 --> 00:05:13.260
You're checking for sufficiency,
not the answer itself.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.310
Another big one is assuming
information that isn't given.

00:05:17.550 --> 00:05:18.659
Stick to the script.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:22.490
When you are checking one statement,
do not peek at the other one.

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:25.580
They must be evaluated
independently first.

00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:30.230
If you see a problem that looks like
it needs a PhD in mathematics to solve,

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:32.240
you are probably on the wrong track.

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:34.790
You are trying to solve it, not check it.

00:05:35.240 --> 00:05:38.300
And lastly, always
consider all possibilities.

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:43.430
If a question mentions integer, think
about positive, negative, and zero.

00:05:43.670 --> 00:05:45.440
Don't leave any stone unturned.

